    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1940-09-19T08:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1940-09-19T08:00:00-05:00" n="159"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d159">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">751G.94/124: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Consul at Hanoi</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Reed</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Hanoi</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1940-09-19T20:00:00+07:00"
                            >September 19, 1940—8 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received September 19—2:40 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>My telegram September 19, 11 [<hi rend="italic">10</hi>] a.m. This afternoon
                    General Nishihara handed the Governor General a letter demanding the Japanese
                    occupation of Hanoi (20,000 troops) and Haiphong (5,000 troops) and 5 airports
                    (with an undisclosed number of troops); unless the demand is accepted, Japanese
                    armed forces will invade Indochina Sunday night September 22, 10 p.m. The
                    Governor General refused the Japanese demand as being outside the scope of the
                    Tokyo–Vichy agreement and is preparing to resist as long as possible.<note
                        n="87" xml:id="d159fn87">For the Department’s instructions to the Ambassador
                        in Japan in connection with this matter, see telegram No. 357, September 19,
                        9 p.m., <ref target="frus1931-41v02#pg_294">
                            <hi rend="italic">Foreign Relations</hi>, Japan, 1931–1941, vol. <hi
                                rend="smallcaps">ii</hi>, p. 294</ref>; for action of the
                        Ambassador, see his memorandum of September 20, <ref
                            target="frus1931-41v02#pg_295">
                            <hi rend="italic">ibid.</hi>, p. 295</ref>.</note>
                </p>
                <p>Sent to Cavite for repetition to the Department, Chungking, Peiping, Hong Kong,
                    Shanghai, Canton. Chungking please repeat to Kunming.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Reed</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
